Customer Churn/Turnover Data¶

Introduction¶

Customer churn (a.k.a customer turnover) is the ratio of customers who decide to leave or stop using a company/business's service or product. Various causes can lead to customer churn, such as customer dissatisfaction, better offers from competitors, change in business or personal needs, or lack of engagement. The Customer Churn data set looks at several attributes of customers who decide to end their relationship with a company. This analysis aims to find potential causes of customer turnover and build a decision tree model to predict churn using a decisino tree classifier so that the company can implement actions that can increase customer retention and overall customer loyalty.

Variable Descriptions

cust_id: A unique identifier for each customer.

region: The geographic region where the customer resides.

tenure: The number of months or years the customer has been with the company.

age: The age of the customer.

marital: Marital status of the customer (e.g., single, married).

address: The number of months or years the customer has lived at their current address.

income: The customer's income level (likely annual). ed: The education level of the customer (e.g., high school, college).

employ: The number of years the customer has been employed.

retire: Whether the customer is retired

gender: The gender of the customer.

reside: The number of people in the household or how long the customer has lived at the current residence.

tollfree: Whether the customer has a toll-free service.

equip: Whether the customer has equipment provided by the company.

callcard: Whether the customer has a calling card.

wireless: Whether the customer has a wireless service.

longmon: Monthly charges for long-distance service.

tollmon: Monthly charges for toll-free service.

equipmon: Monthly charges for equipment services.

cardmon: Monthly charges for calling card services.

wiremon: Monthly charges for wireless services.

longten: Tenure (in months or years) for long-distance services.

tollten: Tenure (in months or years) for toll-free services.

equipten: Tenure (in months or years) for equipment services.

cardten: Tenure (in months or years) for calling card services.

wireten: Tenure (in months or years) for wireless services.

multline: Whether the customer has multiple phone lines.

voice: Whether the customer has voicemail services.

pager: Whether the customer has a pager service.

internet: Whether the customer has internet services.

callid: Whether the customer has caller ID service.

callwait: Whether the customer has call waiting service.

forward: Whether the customer has call forwarding service.

confer: Whether the customer has conference calling service.

ebill: Whether the customer uses electronic billing.

loglong: The logarithm of the customer's long-distance charges (a transformation used in analysis).

lninc: The logarithm of the customer's income (a transformation used in analysis).

custcat: A categorical variable representing the customer category or segment.

churn: Whether the customer has churned (left the service).

Target Variable: churn

1. Data Understanding and Preprocessing¶

In this step, we loaded the customer churn data set and looked at the sturcture of the data to understand the data. Then, we checked for missing values, inpected the data types, and converted all columns with the 'object' data types into 'category' data types for consistency. The cust_id column was deleted because it was not relevant to the analysis. We also examine basic statistics for numerical and categorical features, from which we created boxplots and barcharts.

In the Customer Churn dataset, there were no missing values, and contains numerical and categorical features. The charts included show the relationship between income/age/tenure/region and churn. Income dataset is right-skewed with many outliers, however the comparasion between the customers who stopped using the service and who continued shows that lower income resulted in a increase of turnover. Age and tenure boxplots show that customers from ages 30 to 40 and customers with less tenure ranging from 10 to 30 have a higher turnover rate. Region R2 has a slightly higher turnover rate than R1 and R3, despite R3 having more customers. Overall, the data is not balanced. More customers in this dataset have not stopped using the service.

Model Development¶

To train and develope the decision tree model, we will balance the dataset and split it into training and testing dets. The training model will be used to build the decision tree, and the test set will be used for evaluation.

In [80]:
# Taking steps to balance the train data
# Combine predictors_train and target_train into a single DataFrame
combined_train_df = pd.concat([predictors_train, target_train], axis=1)

# Separate majority and minority classes
# Separate majority and minority classes based on the correct labels
majority_df = combined_train_df[combined_train_df['churn'] == 'N']
minority_df = combined_train_df[combined_train_df['churn'] == 'Y']


# Undersample the majority class randomly
undersampled_majority = majority_df.sample(n=len(minority_df), random_state=5)

# Combine the undersampled majority class and the minority class
undersampled_data = pd.concat([undersampled_majority, minority_df])

# Shuffle the combined DataFrame to ensure randomness
balanced_data = undersampled_data.sample(frac=1, random_state=5)

# Split the balanced_data into predictors_train and target_train
predictors_train = balanced_data.drop(columns=['churn'])
target_train = balanced_data['churn']

The decision tree was evaluated using a classification report, which shows precision, recall, F-1 score, and confusion matrix. The confusion matrix shows that out of the model predicted 179 out of 226 'No' cases correctly, and only 40 out of 76 'Yes' cases correctly. The decision tree has a high precision and recall percentage for the 'No' cases (0.82). However, it needs more work on detecting 'Yes' cases. It can only accurately detect if a customer would stop using the service about half the time.

Conclusion¶

In this report, we built a decision tree model that can potentially predict customer churn. The data understanding, and preprocessing stage, we were able to see the imbalance of the data, outliers, and inital visualizations of potential predictors of churn through barcharts and boxplots. The Model development stage, we were able to balance the data to get a more stable decision tree model. The decision tree model is good at detecting if a customer is not going to be a churner (precision 'N': 0.79, f1-score 'N': 0.82), however it only detects half of the 'Yes' cases accurately (precision 'Y' : 0.54, f1-score 'Y':0.5). The predictors used in this model were: tenure,age, income, longmon, tollmon, equipmon cardmon wiremon region_R2 region_R3, internet_Y, tollfree_Y, equip_Y, wireless_Y, multline_Y, voice_Y, pager_Y, custcat_C2, custcat_C3,custcat_C4. The decision nodes of the tree are internet, tenure, longmon, age, income, and cardmon. If a customer buys interent service ('internet') and how long a customer has had the service (tenure) are the variables with the highest impact on the prediction. A more complex tree may be able to give a more accurate assessment of customers who will churn.
